otball player\n* [[Riley Salmon]] (1976\u2013), American volleyball player\n* [[Riley Skinner]] (1986\u2013), American college football player\n* [[Riley Smith]] (born 1978), American actor\n* [[Riley Smith (American football)]] (1911\u20131999)\n* [[Riley E. Stratton]] (1823\u20131866), American attorney and judge\n* [[Riley Swanson]] (born 1984), American attorney and judge\n* [[Riley Thomson]] (1912\u20131960), American animator\n* [[Riley Voelkel]] (born 1990), American actress\n* [[Riley Wallace]] (born 1941), American basketball coach\n* [[Riley Ware]] (born 1962), American football player\n* [[Riley J. Wilson]] (1871\u20131946), American attorney and legislator\n\n==Fictional characters==\n* [[Riley Andersen]], a character in the movie ''Inside Out''\n* [[Riley Biers]], a character in the ''Twilight'' books\n* [[Riley Dawson]], character in the television series ''Terminator: The Sarah Connor Chronicles''\n* [[Riley Finn]], character in the television series ''Buffy the Vampire Slayer''\n* [[Riley Freeman]], character in the animated television series ''The Boondocks''\n* [[Riley Parker]], a character on ''[[Neighbours]]''\n* [[Riley Poole]], character in the ''National Treasure'' franchise\n* [[Riley Stavros]], a character in ''Degrassi: The Next Generation''\n* Riley Davis, a character in the television series ''[[MacGyver (2016 TV series)|MacGyver]]'', 2016 reboot version\n* [[Riley Blue]], a character in the [[Netflix]] original series '' [[Sense8]]''\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{given name}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Riley (Given Name)}}\n[[Category:English given names]]\n[[Category:English unisex given names]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo/fmt (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Riley_(given_name)"}
{"title_page": "KRLV (AM)", "text_new": "{{Infobox radio station |\n  name                = KRLV |\n  image               = KBAD AM logo.png |\n  city                = [[Las Vegas, Nevada]] |\n  area                = [[Las Vegas metropolitan area]] |\n  branding            = ''920 The Game'' |\n  frequency           = 920 [[kilohertz|kHz]] |\n  airdate             = {{start date and age|1948}} (as KRAM) |\n  format              = [[Sports betting]]|\n  power               = 5,000 [[watt]]s (daytime)<br>500 watts (nighttime) |\n  class               = B |\n  facility_id         = 38448|\n  coordinates         = {{coord|36|11|25|N|115|10|35|W|type:landmark_region:US-NV_source:FCC|display=inline,title}} |\n  callsign_meaning    = '''R'''adio '''L'''as '''V'''egas|\n  former_callsigns    = KRAM (1947\u20131968)<br>KORK (1968\u20131997)<br>KBAD (1997\u20132020)|\n  affiliations        = |\n  sister_stations     = [[KENO]], [[KKGK]], [[KLAV]], [[KOMP (FM)|KOMP]], [[KXPT]], [[KWID]], [[KWWN]]|\n  owner               = [[Lotus Communications]]|\n  webcast             = |\n  website             = [http://www.lvsportsnetwork.com/ LVSportsNetwork.com] |\n}}\n\n'''KRLV''' (920 [[hertz|kHz]]) is a commercial [[AM radio|AM]] [[radio station]] licensed to [[Las Vegas, Nevada]] and is owned by [[Lotus Communications]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/amq?call=KBAD |title=KBAD Facility Record |work=United States [[Federal Communications Commission]], audio division }}</ref>  KBAD airs a [[Sports betting|betting]]-focused [[sports radio|all-sports]] [[radio format]] featuring programming from the locally-based \"BetR Network\". The station's studios and offices are in the unincorporated community of [[Spring Valley, Nevada|Spring Valley]] in [[Clark County, Nevada|Clark County]]<ref>[http://www.lvsportsnetwork.com/contact/ LVSportsNetwork.com/contact]</ref>  The [[transmitter]] is off Wild Jan Drive, northwest of downtown Las Vegas.<ref>[https://radio-locator.com/cgi-bin/patg?id=KBAD-AM&h=N  Radio-Locator.com/KBAD]</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Early years as KORK===\nIn 1951, the station first [[sign-on|signed on]] as '''KORK''' at 1340 [[kilocycle]]s.<ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1952/Radio-NE-Ter-1952-BC-YB.pdf Broadcasting Yearbook 1952 page 191]</ref>  KORK was owned by the Vegas Valley Broadcasting Company, located in the Hotel Thunderbird, and it was powered at only 250 [[watt]]s.\n\nKORK was an [[NBC Red Network]] [[network affiliate|affiliate]], broadcasting NBC's schedule of dramas, comedies, news, sports, [[game show]]s, [[soap opera]]s and [[big band]] remotes.  In 1955, it was bought by the Southwestern Broadcasting Company, which put Channel 3, KORK-TV (later KVBC, now [[KSNV]]) on the air in that same year.  In 1961 KORK got an FM counterpart, 97.1 KORK-FM (now [[KXPT]]).<ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1966/B-Section-Radio-Neb-Ter-BC-YB-1966.pdf Broadcasting Yearbook 1966 page B-91]</ref>\n\n===Move to AM 920===\nIn 1968, KORK, airing a [[Full service (radio format)|full service]] [[middle of the road (music)|Middle of The Road]] format, moved to 920 on the AM dial.  Going to the 920 spot allowed KORK to increase its daytime power to 5,000 watts and slightly boost its nighttime power to 500 watts.<ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1971/B-2-Radio-YB-1971.pdf Broadcasting Yearbook 1971 page B-128]</ref> The 920 facility was first licensed in 1948 as KRAM;<ref name=\"fcc-cards\">{{cite web |title=KORK (KRLV) history cards |url=http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/getimportletter_exh.cgi?import_letter_id=43605 |website=CDBS Public Access |publisher=[[Federal Communications Commission]] |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |format=PDF}}</ref> that call sign concurrently moved to the 1340 license.<ref name=\"fcc-1340cards\">{{cite web |title=KRAM (KKGK) history cards |url=http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/getimportletter_exh.cgi?import_letter_id=44206 |website=CDBS Public Access |publisher=[[Federal Communications Commission]] |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |format=PDF}}</ref>\n\nDuring its heyday under the ownership of [[Donrey Media]], KORK was among the most popular stations in Las Vegas for adults. Its lineup included well-known [[disc jockey]]s, such as Red McIlvaine, Walt Reno and Ron Murphy.\n\nThe simulcast morning [[drive time]] newscasts of KORK/KORK-FM in the 1970s kept both stations high in the ratings. During the latter part of the decade the newsroom was led by news director Bill Buckmaster (now a talk show host at [[KWFM]] in Tucson) and included reporters [[Jackie Glass]] (now a District Court Judge in Las Vegas) and [[Steven L. Herman]], (currently a [[Voice of America]] correspondent in Asia). The trio was frequently heard on [[NBC]] radio network newscasts.  By the early 1980s, KORK became an [[adult standards]] station, airing [[NBC Radio Network|NBC Radio News]] at the beginning of each hour.\n\n===Sports KBAD===\n[[File:Kbad-logo.png|thumb|left|Former logo before the station became an NBC Sports affiliate]]\nKORK changed its call sign to KBAD on April 4, 1997 and began airing an [[sports radio|all-sports]] format. It was known briefly as \"K-BAD AM 920.\"\n\nKBAD was an [[ESPN Radio]] affiliate until March 3, 2008, when that programming was transferred to [[KWWN]]. It then picked up [[Fox Sports Radio]] programming from [[KENO]], which in turn affiliated with [[ESPN Deportes Radio]]. KBAD aired ''[[The Jim Rome Show]]'' until its move to [[CBS Sports Radio]], whose Las Vegas affiliate is [[KXST]].\n\nOn July 1, 2013 KBAD switched affiliations to [[NBC Sports Radio]] and rebranded as \"920 The Game\".<ref>http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84063/las-vegas-sports-affiliation-swap/</ref> On August 5, 2019, KBAD became one of the first terrestrial radio stations in the country dedicated entirely to sports betting, as the station became an affiliate of The BetR Network.<ref name=sportsbettingradio>{{cite news|last=Venta|first=Lance|title=The BetR Network To Debut August 5 On KBAD Las Vegas & WBSS Atlantic City|url=https://radioinsight.com/headlines/179143/the-betr-network-to-debut-august-5-on-kbad-las-vegas-wbss-atlantic-city/|accessdate=July 26, 2019|newspaper=RadioInsight|date=July 24, 2019|quote=The BetR Network will launch on Lotus Broadcasting\u2019s 920 KBAD Las Vegas and Longport Media\u2019s 1490 WBSS Pleasantville/Atlantic City NJ.}}</ref> The call sign was changed to KRLV on March 20, 2020;<ref name=\"fcc-callsigns\">{{cite web |title=Call Sign History (KRLV) |url=http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/call_hist.pl?Facility_id=38448&Callsign=KRLV |website=CDBS Public Access |publisher=[[Federal Communications Commission]] |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> the call sign was transferred from its sister station on 1340, now [[KKGK]].\n\n==Programming==\nKBAD is the [[flagship (broadcasting)|flagship station]] of the sports programs at [[University of Nevada, Las Vegas|UNLV]], including their football and basketball teams.  It is also the flagship station of the [[Las Vegas Aviators]] radio network and carries select games from the [[Sports USA Radio Network]]. The station was previously an affiliate for the [[San Diego Chargers]] and was the flagship station of the former [[Arena Football League (1987\u20132008)|Arena Football League]]'s [[Las Vegas Gladiators]] before they moved to [[Cleveland, Ohio]]. Boxing analyst [[Al Bernstein]] once had a weekday show on KBAD.\n\nThe station is currently an affiliate for the [[Los Angeles Lakers radio networks|Los Angeles Lakers radio network.]] In 2016, the station was made an affiliate for the [[Los Angeles Rams]] [[American football|football]] team.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{AM station data|KRLV}}\n\n{{Lotus Communications}}\n{{Las Vegas Radio}}\n{{Sports Radio Stations in Nevada}}\n\n[[Category:Sports radio stations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Radio stations in the Las Vegas Valley|BAD (AM)]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1948]]\n[[Category:1948 establishments in Nevada]]\n[[Category:NBC Sports Radio stations]]\n[[Category:Lotus Communications stations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox radio station |\n  name                = KRLV |\n  image               = KBAD AM logo.png |\n  city                = [[Las Vegas, Nevada]] |\n  area                = [[Las Vegas metropolitan area]] |\n  branding            = ''920 The Game'' |\n  frequency           = 920 [[kilohertz|kHz]] |\n  airdate             = {{start date and age|1948}} (as KRAM) |\n  format              = [[Sports betting]]|\n  power               = 5,000 [[watt]]s (daytime)<br>500 watts (nighttime) |\n  class               = B |\n  facility_id         = 38448|\n  coordinates         = {{coord|36|11|25|N|115|10|35|W|type:landmark_region:US-NV_source:FCC|display=inline,title}} |\n  callsign_meaning    = '''R'''adio '''L'''as '''V'''egas|\n  former_callsigns    = KRAM (1947\u20131968)<br>KORK (1968\u20131997)<br>KBAD (1997\u20132020)|\n  affiliations        = |\n  sister_stations     = [[KENO]], [[KKGK]], [[KLAV]], [[KOMP (FM)|KOMP]], [[KXPT]], [[KWID]], [[KWWN]]|\n  owner               = [[Lotus Communications]]|\n  webcast             = |\n  website             = [http://www.lvsportsnetwork.com/ LVSportsNetwork.com] |\n}}\n\n'''KRLV''' (920 [[hertz|kHz]]) is a commercial [[AM radio|AM]] [[radio station]] licensed to [[Las Vegas, Nevada]] and is owned by [[Lotus Communications]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/amq?call=KBAD |title=KBAD Facility Record |work=United States [[Federal Communications Commission]], audio division }}</ref>  KBAD airs a [[Sports betting|betting]]-focused [[sports radio|all-sports]] [[radio format]] featuring programming from the locally-based \"BetR Network\". The station's studios and offices are in the unincorporated community of [[Spring Valley, Nevada|Spring Valley]] in [[Clark County, Nevada|Clark County]]<ref>[http://www.lvsportsnetwork.com/contact/ LVSportsNetwork.com/contact]</ref>  The [[transmitter]] is off Wild Jan Drive, northwest of downtown Las Vegas.<ref>[https://radio-locator.com/cgi-bin/patg?id=KBAD-AM&h=N  Radio-Locator.com/KBAD]</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Early years as KORK===\nIn 1951, the station first [[sign-on|signed on]] as '''KORK''' at 1340 [[kilocycle]]s.<ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1952/Radio-NE-Ter-1952-BC-YB.pdf Broadcasting Yearbook 1952 page 191]</ref>  KORK was owned by the Vegas Valley Broadcasting Company, located in the Hotel Thunderbird, and it was powered at only 250 [[watt]]s.\n\nKORK was an [[NBC Red Network]] [[network affiliate|affiliate]], broadcasting NBC's schedule of dramas, comedies, news, sports, [[game show]]s, [[soap opera]]s and [[big band]] remotes.  In 1955, it was bought by the Southwestern Broadcasting Company, which put Channel 3, KORK-TV (later KVBC, now [[KSNV]]) on the air in that same year.  In 1961 KORK got an FM counterpart, 97.1 KORK-FM (now [[KXPT]]).<ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1966/B-Section-Radio-Neb-Ter-BC-YB-1966.pdf Broadcasting Yearbook 1966 page B-91]</ref>\n\n===Move to AM 920===\nIn 1968, KORK, airing a [[Full service (radio format)|full service]] [[middle of the road (music)|Middle of The Road]] format, moved to 920 on the AM dial.  Going to the 920 spot allowed KORK to increase its daytime power to 5,000 watts and slightly boost its nighttime power to 500 watts.<ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1971/B-2-Radio-YB-1971.pdf Broadcasting Yearbook 1971 page B-128]</ref> The 920 facility was first licensed in 1948 as KRAM;<ref name=\"fcc-cards\">{{cite web |title=KORK (KRLV) history cards |url=http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/getimportletter_exh.cgi?import_letter_id=43605 |website=CDBS Public Access |publisher=[[Federal Communications Commission]] |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |format=PDF}}</ref> that call sign concurrently moved to the 1340 license.<ref name=\"fcc-1340cards\">{{cite web |title=KRAM (KKGK) history cards |url=http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/getimportletter_exh.cgi?import_letter_id=44206 |website=CDBS Public Access |publisher=[[Federal Communications Commission]] |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |format=PDF}}</ref>\n\nDuring its heyday under the ownership of [[Donrey Media]], KORK was among the most popular stations in Las Vegas for adults. Its lineup included well-known [[disc jockey]]s, such as Red McIlvaine, Walt Reno and Ron Murphy.\n\nThe simulcast morning [[drive time]] newscasts of KORK/KORK-FM in the 1970s kept both stations high in the ratings. During the latter part of the decade the newsroom was led by news director Bill Buckmaster (now a talk show host at [[KWFM]] in Tucson) and included reporters [[Jackie Glass]] (now a District Court Judge in Las Vegas) and [[Steven L. Herman]], (currently a [[Voice of America]] correspondent in Asia). The trio was frequently heard on [[NBC]] radio network newscasts.  By the early 1980s, KORK became an [[adult standards]] station, airing [[NBC Radio Network|NBC Radio News]] at the beginning of each hour.\n\n===Sports KBAD===\n[[File:Kbad-logo.png|thumb|left|Former logo before the station became an NBC Sports affiliate]]\nKORK changed its call sign to KBAD on April 4, 1997 and began airing an [[sports radio|all-sports]] format. It was known briefly as \"K-BAD AM 920.\"\n\nKBAD was an [[ESPN Radio]] affiliate until until March 3, 2008, when that programming was transferred to [[KWWN]]. It then picked up [[Fox Sports Radio]] programming from [[KENO]], which in turn affiliated with [[ESPN Deportes Radio]]. KBAD aired ''[[The Jim Rome Show]]'' until its move to [[CBS Sports Radio]], whose Las Vegas affiliate is [[KXST]].\n\nOn July 1, 2013 KBAD switched affiliations to [[NBC Sports Radio]] and rebranded as \"920 The Game\".<ref>http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/84063/las-vegas-sports-affiliation-swap/</ref> On August 5, 2019, KBAD became one of the first terrestrial radio stations in the country dedicated entirely to sports betting, as the station became an affiliate of The BetR Network.<ref name=sportsbettingradio>{{cite news|last=Venta|first=Lance|title=The BetR Network To Debut August 5 On KBAD Las Vegas & WBSS Atlantic City|url=https://radioinsight.com/headlines/179143/the-betr-network-to-debut-august-5-on-kbad-las-vegas-wbss-atlantic-city/|accessdate=July 26, 2019|newspaper=RadioInsight|date=July 24, 2019|quote=The BetR Network will launch on Lotus Broadcasting\u2019s 920 KBAD Las Vegas and Longport Media\u2019s 1490 WBSS Pleasantville/Atlantic City NJ.}}</ref> The call sign was changed to KRLV on March 20, 2020;<ref name=\"fcc-callsigns\">{{cite web |title=Call Sign History (KRLV) |url=http://licensing.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/call_hist.pl?Facility_id=38448&Callsign=KRLV |website=CDBS Public Access |publisher=[[Federal Communications Commission]] |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> the call sign was transferred from its sister station on 1340, now [[KKGK]].\n\n==Programming==\nKBAD is the [[flagship (broadcasting)|flagship station]] of the sports programs at [[University of Nevada, Las Vegas|UNLV]], including their football and basketball teams.  It is also the flagship station of the [[Las Vegas Aviators]] radio network and carries select games from the [[Sports USA Radio Network]]. The station was previously an affiliate for the [[San Diego Chargers]] and was the flagship station of the former [[Arena Football League (1987\u20132008)|Arena Football League]]'s [[Las Vegas Gladiators]] before they moved to [[Cleveland, Ohio]]. Boxing analyst [[Al Bernstein]] once had a weekday show on KBAD.\n\nThe station is currently an affiliate for the [[Los Angeles Lakers radio networks|Los Angeles Lakers radio network.]] In 2016, the station was made an affiliate for the [[Los Angeles Rams]] [[American football|football]] team.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{AM station data|KRLV}}\n\n{{Lotus Communications}}\n{{Las Vegas Radio}}\n{{Sports Radio Stations in Nevada}}\n\n[[Category:Sports radio stations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Radio stations in the Las Vegas Valley|BAD (AM)]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1948]]\n[[Category:1948 establishments in Nevada]]\n[[Category:NBC Sports Radio stations]]\n[[Category:Lotus Communications stations]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KRLV_(AM)"}
